    <!-- Section 3: CEI Elimination -->
    <section id="section-3">
        <div class="container">
            <h2>The CEI: Announced, Never Legislated, Eliminated</h2>
            <div class="callout">
                <h3>Canadian Entrepreneurs' Incentive &mdash; Eliminated in Budget 2025</h3>
                <p>Budget 2024 announced a reduced capital gains inclusion rate (33.3% vs. 66.7%) on up to <strong>$2M in lifetime eligible gains</strong> from qualifying CCPC shares (<a href="https://kmss.ca/summary-of-the-new-canadian-entrepreneur-incentive-rules-coming-into-place-for-eligible-capital-gains-starting-january-1-2025/">KMSS</a>). Combined with the $1.25M LCGE, entrepreneurs would have had favourable treatment on up to <strong>$6.25M</strong> in business sale proceeds (<a href="https://ncfacanada.org/guide-lifetime-capital-gains-and-entrepreneurs-incentive/">NCFA</a>). Budget 2025 <strong>scrapped the CEI before it was ever legislated</strong> (<a href="https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/2026-tax-measures-changes-new-9.7022831">CBC, January 2026</a>).</p>
            </div>

            <p>The elimination matters because the CEI was Canada's <em>only proposed</em> exit-side incentive for innovation investors. Budget 2025 simultaneously failed to extend FTS to innovation &mdash; meaning it <strong>removed one exit-side incentive and created no entry-side incentive</strong>. Canada now has zero innovation-specific investor tax incentive of any kind outside the mining FTS.</p>

            <div class="callout-us">
                <h3>Meanwhile, the US Expanded QSBS</h3>
                <p>The One Big Beautiful Bill Act (July 2025) raised the QSBS gross asset threshold from $50M to <strong>$75M</strong>, the exclusion cap from $10M to <strong>$15M</strong>, and introduced graduated exclusions (50%/75%/100% at 3/4/5 years). Between 2012&ndash;2022, approximately <strong>$152 billion</strong> in gains were excluded &mdash; growing from 0.25% to 2.55% of all realised capital gains (<a href="https://home.treasury.gov/system/files/131/WP-127.pdf">US Treasury WP 127</a>; <a href="https://equitablegrowth.org/the-qualified-small-business-stock-exclusion-overwhelmingly-benefits-the-wealthy-and-should-be-reformed-in-2025/">Equitable Growth</a>).</p>
                <p>Taxpayers earning &gt;$1M account for ~75% of excluded gains but only 25% of claims filed. Four states do not conform: California, Pennsylvania, Alabama, Mississippi (<a href="https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/07/one-big-beautiful-bill-act-increases-tax-benefits-for-qualified-small">Holland &amp; Knight</a>).</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

